The term '''post-war''' is generally used for the period after the end of [[World War II]], i.e. after [[1945]]. See also: [[pre-war]]

== Translation ==
[[French]] : [[après]]-[[guerre]]

-----<!-- second transwikification on 19 May 2006 -->

'''Post-War''' is the period of time immediately following the end of a [[war]] and enduring as long as war does not resume. A post-war period can become an [[interwar period]] or interbellum when a war between the same parties resumes at a later date, for example the period between [[November 11]], [[1918]] and [[September 1]], [[1939]] which came between the [[World War I]] and [[World War II]]. By contrast a post-war period marks the cessation of conflict entirely, for example [[Switzerland]] has been in a continuous post-war period since [[1815]].

===Common Usage===
'''Post-War''' is often used in the [[Western]] context to refer to the period of time since the end of World War II, though this is misleading since many nations involved in the Second World War have been involved in wars since. This usage often coincides with the ambiguous term [[post-modern]].

